SIMPLE: loophole
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loophole
<hw>Loop"hole`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A small opening, as in the walls of
fortification, or in the bulkhead of a ship, through which small arms or
other weapons may be discharged at an enemy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hole or aperture that gives a passage, or the
means of escape or evasion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An amibiguity or unintended omission in a law, rule,
regulation, or contract which allows a party to circumvent the intent of
the text and avoid its obligations under certain circumstances. -- used
usually in a negative sense; -- distinguished from <contr>escape
clause</contr> in that the latter usually is included to deliberately
allow evasion of obligation under certain specified and foreseen
circumstances; <as>as, a <ex>loophole</ex> in the law big enough to
drive a truck through</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loopholed</ent>⟦br⟧
